  -- FAQs
  faq1_question = 'What are the benefits of studying in the Netherlands?',
  faq1_answer = 'Key benefits include high-quality education with many English-taught programs, affordable tuition compared to the UK or US, strong international orientation, innovative teaching methods, excellent research facilities, post-study work opportunities, high quality of life, and central location in Europe ideal for travel.',
  faq2_question = 'How much does it cost to study and live in the Netherlands?',
  faq2_answer = 'EU/EEA students pay approximately €2,200 per year in tuition, while non-EU/EEA students pay €6,000-32,000 depending on the program. Living expenses range from €800-1,750 per month depending on the city, with Amsterdam being the most expensive and smaller cities more affordable.',
  faq3_question = 'Do I need to speak Dutch to study in the Netherlands?',
  faq3_answer = 'No, there are over 2,100 English-taught programs, and most Dutch people speak excellent English. While not necessary for your studies, learning some basic Dutch can enrich your daily life experience and may be beneficial if you plan to work in the Netherlands after graduating.',
  faq4_question = 'Can I work while studying in the Netherlands?',
  faq4_answer = 'EU/EEA students can work without restrictions. Non-EU/EEA students can work either part-time (max 16 hours per week) during the academic year OR full-time during summer months (June-August). Employers must arrange a work permit, but many student jobs are available, especially in larger cities.',
  faq5_question = 'What are the visa requirements for studying in the Netherlands?',
  faq5_answer = 'EU/EEA students only need a valid ID/passport and must register with the local municipality. Non-EU/EEA students need an entry visa (MVV) and residence permit, requiring acceptance from a recognized institution, sufficient financial resources, health insurance, and a clear criminal record.',
  faq6_question = 'Are there scholarships available for international students?',
  faq6_answer = 'Yes, scholarships are available through the Dutch government (Orange Knowledge Programme, Holland Scholarship), individual universities, and external organizations. Most are merit-based and competitive, with application deadlines usually several months before programs begin.',
  faq7_question = 'What is the difference between research universities and universities of applied sciences?',
  faq7_answer = 'Research universities (WO) offer more theoretical, research-oriented education preparing students for independent research or professional roles requiring scientific knowledge. Universities of applied sciences (HBO) provide practical, profession-oriented education preparing students directly for specific careers or industries.',
  faq8_question = 'What are the post-graduation opportunities in the Netherlands?',
  faq8_answer = 'Graduates can apply for the Orientation Year permit, allowing them to stay for up to 12 months to find a job or start a business without needing employer sponsorship. The Netherlands has a favorable highly skilled migrant program and many international companies seeking English-speaking graduates, particularly in technology, engineering, and business sectors.'
